As I tried to update to MonoGame 3.3 I encountered some strange behavior. I'm really unsure if this is a bug or me misusing something, but since it worked fine under 3.2 and fails in 3.3 now... My guess would be some different handling within the SpriteBatch class, but I have no idea of the actual Framework code at all.

First of all: I'm using the "Advanced Zima 2D Shadows" (MonoGame version), compiled with the 3.3 Pipeline Tool on Windows and using the 3.2 assemblies of MonoGame (in my actual game) everything just worked fine:
![tm_shader_working](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/11522235/6690867/5137444e-ccc3-11e4-928f-1425daa8a052.png)

Now I switched to the 3.3 assemblies and got this result (without any other changes):
![tm_shader_failing](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/11522235/6690878/654d230e-ccc3-11e4-9839-6db971301e4d.png)

After some research I could narrow down the Problem to a 2x multi blend shader that doesn't seem to do it's job anymore.
![tm_shader_failinginfo](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/11522235/6690899/7ec7a426-ccc3-11e4-9122-095c85eb1a25.png)
As you can see the lightmap is still being created correctly, but the blending part just blackens everything out (I used my main SpriteBatch to simply draw the lightmap instead of blending it with the underlying texture as done in the first picture). In the actual code there is a separate SpriteBatch set to use the multi blend shader to draw both textures.
Note: The rocks around the player/placeholder changed since I restarted/rebuilt the game each time and therefore the map was randomly rebuilt each time.

Since I'm quite confused now whether it's my bad or not I couldn't help myself besides posting this as an issue here. I am working on a Linux platform and even tried the WinGL assembly, but I still got this (unwanted) result.

The c# code where this issue occurs looks like this (completly from the shading system mentioned above):

```
this.LightBlender.Parameters["MixFactor"].SetValue(mixFactor0to1);
graphics.GraphicsDevice.SetRenderTarget(renderTarget);
spriteBatch.Begin(SpriteSortMode.Immediate, BlendState.AlphaBlend, SamplerState.LinearClamp, null, RasterizerState.CullNone, this.LightBlender);
graphics.GraphicsDevice.Textures[1] = light;
graphics.GraphicsDevice.Textures[1].GraphicsDevice.SamplerStates[1] = SamplerState.LinearClamp;
spriteBatch.Draw(underlyingTexture, Vector2.Zero, Color.White);
spriteBatch.End();
```

Sorry, if this is my issue and not yours, but I don't quite understand shaders yet and I didn't make any changes except the assembly-version I use (both are marked as 3.1.2.0 though).
Oh, while writing this I remembered: The "old" assembly was not the official 3.2 one. It was the one from the "MonoDevelop Alpha Add-In Package" (.mpack) that @cra0zy (or however his name is spelled, sorry) posted. I'm unsure which version this actually is since they are all marked as 3.1.2.0...

I decided to give a try to the PSM part and when I tryed to draw simple texture I ended up with null pointer exception it turns out that inside SpriteBatcher method DrawVertexArray I had to add the following code in order to work : 

if(effect == null) {
  var vertexCount = end - start;
            _device._graphics.DrawArrays(DrawMode.Triangles, start / 2 \* 3, vertexCount / 2 \* 3);
} else {

 var passes = effect.CurrentTechnique.Passes;
            foreach (var pass in passes)
            {
                pass.Apply();
                _device._graphics.DrawArrays(DrawMode.Triangles, start / 2 \* 3, vertexCount / 2 \* 3);
            }
}

I hope that can help someone :)

I use latest release MonoGame 3.2 on windows (windows DirectX project).
I have this texture:
![origin](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/11148445/6482217/e0ab3468-c274-11e4-9e63-81a234e4541d.png)
When i write code like this:

```
byte[] pixelData = new byte[width * height * 4];
testTexture.GetData<byte>(pixelData);
testTexture.SetData<byte>(pixelData);      // now texture is corrupted
```

texture is getting spoiled.
 ![spoiled](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/11148445/6482219/e52e6f96-c274-11e4-8628-11fc2359cf15.png)
But if i use int[] to get data, everything is ok:

```
int[] pixelData = new int[width * height];
testTexture.GetData<int>(pixelData);
testTexture.SetData<int>(pixelData);     // it still the same (OK)
```

This approach works fine too:

```
int[] pixelData = new int[width * height];
testTexture.GetData<int>(pixelData);
testTexture.SetData<byte>(IntArrayToByteArray(pixelData));       // still OK
```

Here is my convert method:

```
static byte[] IntArrayToByteArray(int[] intArray)
{
      byte[] result = new byte[intArray.Length * sizeof(int)];
      Buffer.BlockCopy(intArray, 0, result, 0, result.Length);
      return result;
 }
```

So i guess Texture2D.GetData<byte> returns incorrect result.
